{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% set headline = card_data.headline %}
{% set managers = card_data.managers %}
{% set marginal = card_data.marginal_codes %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/p1.css">
{% endblock %}

{% macro pct(x) %}{{ "%.1f"|format(x * 100) }}%{% endmacro %}

{% macro band_row(m) %}
<article class="p1-row{% if m.action == 'review' %} p1-row--review{% endif %}"
         data-floor="{{ m.floor }}" data-anchor="{{ m.anchor }}" data-ceil="{{ m.ceil }}"
         data-naive="{{ m.naive_ols }}" data-domain-min="0"
         data-domain-max="{{ card_data.meta.alloc_cap }}">
  <header class="p1-row__head">
    <span class="p1-row__name">{{ m.name }}</span>
    <span class="p1-row__meta">group {{ m.group }} &middot; {{ m.months }} months</span>
    <span class="advisory-band" data-band="{{ m.advisory_band }}">{{ m.advisory_band }}</span>
    {% if m.fund_or_not %}<span class="p1-chip p1-chip--fund" title="band floor at 0%">fund-or-not</span>{% endif %}
  </header>
  <div class="interval-stat" data-domain="weight"
       data-lo="{{ m.floor }}" data-point="{{ m.anchor }}" data-hi="{{ m.ceil }}"
       aria-label="Advisory band {{ pct(m.floor) }} to {{ pct(m.ceil) }}, anchor {{ pct(m.anchor) }}">
    <span class="interval-stat__label">Advisory band (share of book)</span>
    <span class="interval-stat__value">{{ pct(m.floor) }}&ndash;{{ pct(m.ceil) }}</span>
    <div class="interval-stat__rail p1-band__rail">
      <div class="interval-stat__band"></div>
      <div class="interval-stat__point" title="median anchor {{ pct(m.anchor) }}"></div>
      <div class="p1-naive" title="point optimizer (raw OLS) {{ pct(m.naive_ols) }}"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="p1-shared-axis" aria-hidden="true"><span>0%</span><span>{{ "%.0f"|format(card_data.meta.alloc_cap * 100) }}% manager cap</span></div>
    <span class="interval-stat__range" data-state-range>
      10th&ndash;90th percentile of posterior-draw weights &middot;
      anchor {{ pct(m.anchor) }} &middot;
      <span class="p1-naive-note">point optimizer {{ pct(m.naive_ols) }}</span>
    </span>
  </div>
  <div class="p1-dial" data-dial="{{ m.code }}">
    <span class="p1-dial__label">Skepticism dial (&tau;-scale)</span>
    <div class="p1-dial__options">
      {% for f in m.fan %}
      <button type="button" class="p1-dial__btn{% if f.scale == 1.0 %} p1-dial__btn--active{% endif %}"
              data-scale="{{ f.scale }}" data-floor="{{ f.floor }}" data-anchor="{{ f.anchor }}"
              data-ceil="{{ f.ceil }}" aria-pressed="{{ 'true' if f.scale == 1.0 else 'false' }}">
        &times;{{ "%.1f"|format(f.scale) }}</button>
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="p1-dial__readout" data-dial-readout aria-live="polite">
      &times;1 &tau;: band {{ pct(m.floor) }}&ndash;{{ pct(m.ceil) }}</p>
  </div>
</article>
{% endmacro %}

{% block demo_content %}
<section class="p1-intro">
  <p class="p1-headline">
    {{ headline.name }} gets
    <strong>{{ pct(headline.naive_ols) }}</strong> of the book from the point optimizer on its raw
    OLS alpha &mdash; but its honest band is
    <strong>{{ pct(headline.floor) }}&ndash;{{ pct(headline.ceil) }}</strong>: the naive weight sits
    <strong>above the entire range</strong> the posterior evidence supports. The width of a band is
    the honesty; this page decides <em>how much</em>, after the skill model asked <em>how good</em>.
  </p>
  <p class="p1-disclose">
    SYNTHETIC: every input is a reviewed skill posterior on the simulator roster. The demo
    holds <strong>residual volatility constant at 8%/yr</strong> for every manager, so band
    differences are driven purely by the posteriors; the live build substitutes each manager's
    de-smoothed residual volatility from the uncertainty-honest tear-sheet method. The demo draws also
    <strong>treat manager posteriors as independent</strong>; the live joint-posterior draws carry
    group-level dependence and widen the bands slightly.
  </p>
</section>

<aside class="p1-exhibit" aria-label="What this exhibit shows">
  <h2 class="p1-exhibit__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <div class="p1-exhibit__block">
    <h3 class="p1-exhibit__sub">What you are looking at</h3>
    <p>
      One row per manager, ordered by band anchor. Each row's bar is the
      <strong>advisory band</strong> &mdash; the 10th&ndash;90th percentile of that manager's weight
      across {{ "{:,}".format(card_data.meta.n_draws) }} posterior draws &mdash; with the median
      anchor as the interior tick. The separate marker is the
      <strong>point optimizer</strong> weight on raw OLS alphas: where it sits relative to the band
      is a per-manager verdict on the naive method. {{ headline.name }}'s marker sits above its
      whole band; across the book the top-3 concentration is
      <strong>{{ pct(headline.top3_naive) }}</strong> under the point optimizer versus
      <strong>{{ pct(headline.top3_anchor) }}</strong> at the band anchors.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="p1-exhibit__block">
    <h3 class="p1-exhibit__sub">How to read it</h3>
    <ul class="p1-exhibit__list">
      <li><strong>The band bar</strong> &mdash; the range of allocations the evidence supports;
        the tick inside is the median anchor, never shown alone (no bare points).</li>
      <li><strong>The point-optimizer marker</strong> &mdash; the cautionary contrast; a weight
        outside the band is a sizing-review trigger. It is never exported as an actionable number.</li>
      <li><strong>The band pill</strong> (review / minimum / standard / conviction) &mdash; the
        advisory label carried from the skill assessment.</li>
      <li><strong>The fund-or-not chip</strong> &mdash; on names whose band floor is 0%: the
        evidence is consistent both with a small allocation and with none.</li>
      <li><strong>The skepticism dial</strong> &mdash; turn the house &tau;-prior scale up and the
        bands widen; the states are precomputed at &times;0.5/&times;1/&times;2.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="p1-exhibit__bridge">
      The full methodology &mdash; with the math and a reference implementation &mdash; is in the
      <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">method spec</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</aside>

<section class="p1-rows" data-rows>
  {% for m in managers %}{{ band_row(m) }}{% endfor %}
</section>

<section class="p1-marginal">
  <h2 class="p1-marginal__title">Fund-or-not names</h2>
  <p class="p1-marginal__body">
    {{ marginal | length }} funded managers carry a band floor of exactly 0%
    in this book. In a nontrivial fraction of posterior draws the rule allocates them
    nothing. The chart says so, rather than hiding it behind a confident 1.5%. This is a
    judgement call routed to the redeem/re-up review &mdash; <strong>never</strong> a mechanical
    redemption.
  </p>
</section>

<div class="power-gate">
  <span class="power-gate__title">power gate</span>
  <p class="power-gate__reason">
    Bands render at any track length &mdash; width carries the honesty. <em>Decisive</em> bands
    (floors clear of zero, the point optimizer reliably beaten) need the favourable regime:
    realistically <strong>T &ge; 48</strong> and true skill dispersion <strong>&ge; 2%/yr</strong>.
    At 1% dispersion and T = 36 the posterior barely separates managers, so this page shows wide
    bands, not decisive ones. The <strong>policy-regret study</strong> that will license decisive
    language across the grid is <strong>pending</strong>; until it lands,
    <strong>every band on this page is advisory</strong>.
  </p>
</div>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>The band is the image of the skill posterior under the allocation rule: draw an alpha vector from
each manager's posterior, size it with a long-only edge-over-variance rule (weight proportional to
the positive part of alpha over residual variance, fully invested, capped at
{{ pct(card_data.meta.alloc_cap) }} per manager), and repeat
{{ "{:,}".format(card_data.meta.n_draws) }} times. The 10th&ndash;90th percentile of the resulting
weight distribution is the advisory band; the median is the anchor. Nothing tunes the band to look
honest &mdash; it inherits honesty from the posterior and narrows mechanically as the evidence
tightens (see the matched-record comparison in the article).</p>
<p>A point-estimate optimizer fed noisy alphas is an estimation-error maximizer: it allocates most
aggressively exactly where the inputs are least reliable. The naive marker is that method,
displayed as a cautionary contrast &mdash; not a product. Where a band is wide, that width is the
finding, not a failure to conclude.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/p1-allocation.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
